<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-059-536  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 059 536.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Data Communications  Feb 1989 v18 n2 p88(14).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Coming soon to an outlet near you: premises fiber. (includesrelated article on do's and don'ts for optical fiber and on how toterminate a fiber with an ST connector)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mier, Edwin E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A Data Communications magazine survey reveals that six out of 10end users are already using premises fiber, and 80 percent ofthose surveyed plan to install premises fiber within the next 18months.andP;  Key factors involving the installation of premises fiberinclude the specification of fiber and connector characteristics,deciding whether to standardize and deciding who will deploy thefiber.andP;  The recommended fiber type is multimode, 62.5-125-micronfiber because it is endorsed by various standards bodies andsupports a 45M-bps data rate to 11 miles.andP;  The ST connector isrecommended as the best choice in connectors because it offers anoverall 2 dB loss per connection, but typically has only 0.5 dBloss.andP;  The ST is constructed of ceramic and metal, providing moredurability.andP;  Other fiber and connector types, installationdecisions and survey results are discussed at length.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber opticsCustomer Premises EquipmentUser SurveyConnectorsData CommunicationsHardware Selection.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Users in the process of selecting or installing premises fiber.andO;(graph)Users planning to deploy or consider premises fiber in the next 18months. (graph)Breakdown of respondents to Data Communications magazine survey.andO;(graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>